  {layer_group_id: nil, name: "Ecosystem-based Adaptation Priority Areas (Kruger to Canyons) ", slug: "south-africa_eba-adnm", layer_type: "layer", zindex: nil, active: false, order: nil, color: nil, info: "{\"description\":\"Ecosystem based Adaptation (EbA) priority areas can be used to identify the location where restoration and land management activities can be concentrated to maximize the potential for natural ecosystems to contribute to building social and ecological resilience to climate change. This layer highlights the areas that are critical for people dependent on natural resources for their livelihoods; important for sustaining viable and robust ecological systems; essential for delivering ecosystem services; and supportive for ecosystem based adaptation which support the overall socio-ecological system. By assessing local level vulnerability, EbA activity areas can be identified through the intersection of ecological infrastructure, biodiversity priorities, climate resilience and social priorities. Together these assessments spatially identify priority areas that will be linked with site specific implementation activities.<p>The EbA priority areas identify ecosystems that deliver valuable water resources for people and are important for water production, flood attenuation, erosion control and maintaining water quality. Biodiversity priorities consider other ecological infrastructure, e.g. the presence of threatened habitats, the protection of high biodiversity areas, and areas important for supporting natural resilience to climate stresses and shocks. Riparian corridors, coastal corridors, areas of high plant endemism, refuge sites and large unfragmented landscapes are the features that support climate resilience in the landscape. The socio-economic priority areas are defined by population density, income and reliance on natural resources. Evaluating and prioritizing these areas can improve our understanding on how our natural resources in a functional and healthy state and supported by enhanced socio economic conditions can reduce a communitys vulnerability to climate change.\",\"source\":\"<p>CSA (Conservation South Africa). 2015. Kruger to Canyons, available online at www.southafrica.conservation.org.\", \"link\":\"www.southafrica.conservation.org\" }", layer_provider: "raster", css: "#eba_k2c {\r\n  raster-opacity:1;\r\n\traster-colorizer-default-mode: linear; \r\n\traster-colorizer-default-color: transparent; \r\n\traster-colorizer-epsilon: 0.01;\r\n\traster-colorizer-stops:  \r\n    \tstop(-9999, transparent)\r\n    \tstop(0, transparent)\r\n    \tstop(63,#ffffe5)\r\n        stop(77,#fff7bc)\r\n        stop(92, #fee391)\r\n    \tstop(105,#fec44f)\r\n    \tstop(117,#fe9929)\r\n        stop(134,#ec7014)\r\n        stop(157,#cc4c02)\r\n        stop(188,#993404)\r\n        stop(350,#662506)\r\n}", interactivity: "", opacity: 1.0, query: "select the_raster_webmercator from eba_k2c", locate_layer: true, icon_class: nil, published: true, legend: "{\"min\":\"low\",\"max\":\"high\",\"type\":\"choropleth\", \"bucket\": \r\n[           \"#ffffe5\",\r\n            \"#fff7bc\",\r\n            \"#fee391\",\r\n            \"#fec44f\",\r\n            \"#fe9929\",\r\n            \"#ec7014\",\r\n            \"#cc4c02\",\r\n            \"#993404\",\r\n            \"#662506\"\r\n          ]\r\n        }", zoom_max: 100, zoom_min: 0, dashboard_order: nil, download: false, dataset_shortname: "CSA (Conservation South Africa). 2015. Climate Change Vulnerability Assessment: Alfred Nzo Municipality. Technical report, available online at www.southafrica.conservation.org", dataset_source_url: "http://www.conservation.org/publications/Documents/CI_ANDM-Climate-Vulnerability-Assessment.pdf ", title: "Ecosystem-based Adaptation Priority Areas (Kruger to Canyons)", start_date: nil, end_date: nil, spatial_resolution: "", spatial_resolution_units: "", temporal_resolution: "", temporal_resolution_units: "", data_units: "", update_frequency: "", version: "", processing: "", description: "Ecosystem based Adaptation (EbA) priority areas can be used to identify the location where restoration and land management activities can be concentrated to maximize the potential for natural ecosystems to contribute to building social and ecological resilience to climate change. This layer highlights the areas that are critical for people dependent on natural resources for their livelihoods; important for sustaining viable and robust ecological systems; essential for delivering ecosystem services; and supportive for ecosystem based adaptation which support the overall socio-ecological system. By assessing local level vulnerability, EbA activity areas can be identified through the intersection of ecological infrastructure, biodiversity priorities, climate resilience and social priorities. Together these assessments spatially identify priority areas that will be linked with site specific implementation activities.<p>The EbA priority areas identify ecosystems that deliver valuable water resources for people and are important for water production, flood attenuation, erosion control and maintaining water quality. Biodiversity priorities consider other ecological infrastructure, e.g. the presence of threatened habitats, the protection of high biodiversity areas, and areas important for supporting natural resilience to climate stresses and shocks. Riparian corridors, coastal corridors, areas of high plant endemism, refuge sites and large unfragmented landscapes are the features that support climate resilience in the landscape. The socio-economic priority areas are defined by population density, income and reliance on natural resources. Evaluating and prioritizing these areas can improve our understanding on how our natural resources in a functional and healthy state and supported by enhanced socio economic conditions can reduce a communitys vulnerability to climate change."},
